\begin_layout Subsection
Parabola Method Via Epigraph
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In previous sections, we have discussed cutting plane methods that maintain
 a region that contains the minimizer 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{*}$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

.
 The proof of such a cutting plane method relies on the following inequality
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
f(x)>f(x^{*})\geq f(x)+\left\langle \nabla f(x),x^{*}-x\right\rangle \label{eq:epigraph_cuttingplane-1}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Notice that the left-hand side is a strict inequality (unless we already
 solved the problem).
 We infer a halfspace containing the optimum, namely 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left\langle \nabla f(x),x^{*}-x\right\rangle \le0.
\]

\end_inset

As the algorithm proceeds, we find a new point 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{\new}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x^{\new})<f(x)$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore, the original inequality can be strengthened to 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f(x^{(new)})>f(x)+\left\langle \nabla f(x),x^{*}-x\right\rangle 
\]

\end_inset

or 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left\langle \nabla f(x),x^{*}-x\right\rangle <-(f(x)-f(x^{(new)})).
\]

\end_inset

This suggests we should move earlier halfspaces and thereby reduce the measure
 of the next set.
 We expect merely updating the halfspaces can improve the convergence rate
 from 
\begin_inset Formula $1-\frac{\mu}{L}$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $1-\sqrt{\frac{\mu}{L}}$
\end_inset

 because of the right diagram in Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:geometric_descent-1"

\end_inset

.
 An efficient way to manage all this information is to directly maintain
 a region that contains 
\begin_inset Formula $(x^{*},f(x^{*}))$
\end_inset

.
 Now, we can view the inequality 
\begin_inset Formula $f(y)\geq f(x)+\left\langle \nabla f(x),y-x\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 as a cutting plane of the epigraph of 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 and we do not need to update previous cutting planes anymore.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The next algorithm is an epigraph cutting plane method.
\end_layout

